🧠 Part 1 — What is Control Plane REALLY?

You already know:

👉 “Control Plane = Brain”

But that’s shallow.

🔥 Real Definition:

Control Plane is a distributed decision-making system that:

• Accepts desired state
• Stores it
• Continuously reconciles actual state to match it

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Think of Swiggy / Zomato system:

• You place order → API Server
• System stores order → etcd
• Assign delivery partner → Scheduler
• Monitor delivery → Controller

🧠 Control Plane Components

We go deep into each:

1️⃣ API Server (The Gatekeeper)

What it does:

• Entry point for ALL requests
• Validates requests
• Authenticates & authorizes
• Updates cluster state

Internal Flow:

When you run:

kubectl get pods

Flow:

Request → API Server
Auth check
RBAC check
Fetch from etcd
Return response
🔥 Important Insight:

👉 No component talks directly to etcd except API Server

2️⃣ etcd (The Brain Memory)

What it is:

• Distributed key-value store
• Stores entire cluster state

Example Data:
{
  "pod": "nginx",
  "status": "Running",
  "node": "worker-1"
}

🔥 Critical Facts:

• Uses RAFT consensus algorithm
• Strong consistency
• If etcd is DOWN → cluster is DEAD

⚠️ Production Insight:

👉 Always take etcd backups

3️⃣ Scheduler (Decision Maker)

What it does:

👉 Decides which node runs a pod

How it decides:

Step 1: Filtering
→ Remove unsuitable nodes

Step 2: Scoring
→ Rank best node

Factors:

• CPU / Memory
• Node affinity
• Taints & tolerations
• Resource availability

🔥 Important:

Scheduler does NOT create pods
→ It only assigns nodes

4️⃣ Controller Manager (The Watcher)

What it does:

👉 Ensures desired state = actual state

Example:

You say:

replicas: 3

Reality:

Only 2 pods running

Controller:

👉 Creates 1 more pod

Types of Controllers:

• Deployment Controller
• ReplicaSet Controller
• Node Controller

🔥 Key Concept:

👉 Reconciliation Loop (runs continuously)

🧠 Full Flow (VERY IMPORTANT)

Let’s combine everything:

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
Internal Flow:
kubectl → API Server
API Server → validates + stores in etcd
Controller Manager → sees desired state
Scheduler → assigns node
kubelet → creates pod
